n \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Some older cards used the term \ldblquote casting cost\rdblquote  to describe the mana cost of a spell. In general, cards that were printed with the term \ldblquote casting cost\rdblquote  now use the term \ldblquote mana cost.\rdblquote  Cards that used the term \ldblquote total casting cost\rdblquote  now use the term \ldblquote converted mana cost.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Change a Target\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 The target of a spell or ability can change only to another legal target. If the target can\rquote t change to another legal target, the original target is unchanged. Changing a spell or ability\rquote s target can\rquote t change its mode. You can change the target of a spell or ability only if an effect tells you to change its target. See rule 415.7, \ldblquote Changing Targets.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Characteristics\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 An object\rquote s characteristics are name, mana cost, color, type, subtype, supertype, expansion symbol, abilities, rules text, power, and toughness. Characteristics don\rquote t include any other information, such as whether a permanent is tapped, a spell or permanent\rquote s controller, a spell\rquote s target, what an Aura enchants, and so on. See rule 201, \ldblquote Characteristics.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Characteristic-Setting Ability\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Some objects have static abilities which state that that object \ldblquote has\rdblquote  one or more characteristics; \ldblquote is\rdblquote  a particular type, supertype, subtype, or color; or that one or more of its characteristics \ldblquote is\rdblquote  or \ldblquote are\rdblquote  a particular value. These abilities are characteristic-setting abilities. See rule 405.2.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Characteristic-Setting Effect\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 An effect from a characteristic-setting ability is a characteristic-setting effect. See rule 405.2.\par }\pard \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\insrsid215233 \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Cleanup Step\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Cleanup is the second and final step of the end phase. Spells and abilities may be played during this step only if the conditions for any state-based effects exist or if any abilities have triggered. In that case, the step repeats. See rule 314, \ldblquote Cleanup Step.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Collector Number\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Some card sets feature collector numbers. This information is printed in the form [card number]/[total cards in the set], immediately following the legal text. These numbers have no effect on game play. See rule 211, \ldblquote Collector Number.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Color\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 The only colors in the }{\b\insrsid215233 Magic}{\insrsid215233  game are white, blue, black, red, and green. An object can be one or more of those colors or it can be colorless. \ldblquote Colorless\rdblquote  isn\rquote t a color; neither are \ldblquote artifact,\rdblquote  \ldblquote land,\rdblquote  \ldblquote brown,\rdblquote  \ldblquote gold,\rdblquote  and so on. See rule 203.2.\par      An object\rquote s color is determined by the color(s) of the mana symbols in its mana cost.\par      Effects may change an object\rquote s color. If an effect gives an object a new color, the new color replaces all previous colors the object had.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Colorless\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 An object with no color is colorless. Lands are colorless because they have no mana cost. Artifacts are colorless because they have no colored mana in their mana costs. Face-down creatures are colorless due to the effects that turn them face down. A colorless object can be given a color by an effect. See rule 203.2.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Colorless mana\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Numeral symbols (such as \{1\}) and variable symbols (such as \{X\}) can represent colorless mana if they appear in the effect of a spell or ability that reads, \ldblquote add [mana symbol] to your mana pool,\rdblquote  or something similar. See rule 104.3d.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Combat Damage\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Combat damage is dealt during the combat damage step of the combat phase by attacking creatures and blocking creatures. It doesn\rquote t include damage dealt by spells and abilities during the combat phase. See rule 310, \ldblquote Combat Damage Step.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Combat Damage Step\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 The combat damage step is the fourth step of the combat phase. Attacking and blocking creatures deal damage in the combat damage step. A player may play spells and abilities during this step whenever he or she has priority. See rule 310, \ldblquote Combat Damage Step.\rdblquote  If any attacking or blocking creature has first strike (see rule 502.2) or double strike (see rule 502.28), there are two combat damage steps.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Combat Phase\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Combat is the third phase of the turn. The combat phase has five steps: beginning of combat, declare attackers, declare blockers, combat damage, and end of combat. See rules 306\endash 311.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Comes into Play\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 A permanent comes into play when the card or token representing it is moved into the in-play zone. A permanent whose type or controller changes doesn\rquote t \ldblquote come into play.\rdblquote \par      Permanents come into play untapped and under the control of whoever put them into play.\par      When a permanent comes into play, first apply any replacement effects, then apply continuous effects, then check to determine if the current form of the permanent generates any triggered abilities.\par }\pard\plain \s28\ql \li400\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin400\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\insrsid215233 Example:}{\insrsid215233  If an instruction causes something to come into play tapped, it isn\rquote t put into play untapped and then tapped.\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Concede\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 A player may concede a game at any time. A player who concedes leaves the game immediately. He or she loses the game. See rule 102.\par }\pard \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\insrsid215233 \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Constructed\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 In constructed play, each player needs his or her own deck of at least sixty cards, small items to represent any tokens and counters, and some way to clearly track life totals. A constructed deck can have any number of basic land cards and no more than four of any card with a particular English name other than basic land cards. See rule 100.2.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Continuous Effect\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Continuous effects are usually active as long as the permanent with the associated static ability remains in play or the object with the associated static ability remains in the appropriate zone. A spell or ability can also create a continuous effect that doesn\rquote t depend on a permanent; these last as long as the spell or ability specifies. See rule 418, \ldblquote Continuous Effects.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Continuous Artifact (Obsolete)\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Some older cards used the term \ldblquote continuous artifact\rdblquote  on the card\rquote s type line. They were artifacts without activated abilities. Cards that were printed with the term \ldblquote continuous artifact\rdblquote  now simply use \ldblquote artifact.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Control, Controller\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 A permanent\rquote s controller is whoever put it into play unless the spell or ability that put the permanent into play states otherwise. Other effects can later change a permanent\rquote s controller.\par      A spell or activated ability on the stack is controlled by whoever played it. A copy of a spell is controlled by the player who put it on the stack. A triggered ability on the stack is controlled by the player who controlled its source at the time it triggered.\par      Objects in zones other than in play or the stack have no controller. If anything asks for the controller of an object that doesn\rquote t have a controller, use its owner instead.\par \par Controlling Another Player\rquote s Turn\par One card (Mindslaver) allows a player to control another player\rquote s turn. The controller of another player\rquote s turn makes all choices and decisions that player is allowed to make or is told to make during that turn by rules or by any objects. A player doesn\rquote t lose life due to mana burn while another player controls his or her turn. See rule 507, \ldblquote Controlling Another Player\rquote s Turn.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Converted Mana Cost\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 The converted mana cost of an object is the total amount of mana in its mana cost, regardless of color. If an object has no mana cost, its converted mana cost is 0. See rule 203, \ldblquote Mana Cost and Color.\rdblquote \par }\pard\plain \s28\ql \li400\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin400\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\insrsid215233 Example:}{\insrsid215233  An Air Elemental has a mana cost of \{3\}\{U\}\{U\} and a converted mana cost of 5.\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Copiable Values\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 An object\rquote s \ldblquote copiable values\rdblquote  are the values that are printed on the object, as modified by other copy effects, plus any values set for face-down spells or permanents. Other effects (including type-changing effects) and counters are not copied. See rules 503.2 and 503.3.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Copy\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 A \ldblquote copy\rdblquote  of an object is an object whose copiable values have been set to those of the first object. See rule 503, \ldblquote Copying Objects.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Cost\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Playing spells and activated abilities requires paying a cost. Most costs are paid in mana, but they may also include paying life, tapping or sacrificing permanents, discarding cards, and so on.\par      A player can\rquote t pay a cost unless he or she has the necessary resources to pay it fully. For example, a player with only 1 life can\rquote t pay a cost of 2 life, and a permanent that\rquote s already tapped can\rquote t be tapped to pay a cost. See rule 203, \ldblquote Mana Cost and Color,\rdblquote  and rule 403, \ldblquote Activated Abilities.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Counter\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Counter has two meanings in the }{\b\insrsid215233 Magic}{\insrsid215233  game.\par      1. To counter a spell or ability is to cancel it, removing it from the stack. It doesn\rquote t resolve and none of its effects occur. A countered spell is put into its owner\rquote s graveyard. See rule 414, \ldblquote Countering Spells and Abilities.\rdblquote \par      2. A counter is a marker placed on an object, either modifying its characteristics or interacting with an effect. A +X/+Y counter on a permanent, where X and Y are numbers, adds X to that permanent\rquote s power and Y to that permanent\rquote s toughness. These bonuses are added after permanent-type changing effects and before other power and toughness changing effects. Similarly, -X/-Y counters subtract from power and toughness. Counters with the same name or description are interchangeable. Counters may also be given to players. For information about poison counters, see rule 102.3d.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Counts As (Obsolete)\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Some older cards were printed with text stating that the card \ldblquote counts as\rdblquote  something. As far as the game rules and other cards are concerned the card is that thing. (Newer }{\b\insrsid215233 Magic}{\insrsid215233  cards use \ldbl