t\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Declare Attackers Step\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 The declare attackers step is the second step of the combat phase. The active player declares attackers during this step. Then the active player gets priority and players may play spells and abilities. See rule 308, \ldblquote Declare Attackers Step.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Declare Blockers\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 To declare blockers, the defending player chooses a set of creatures that will block and pays any costs they require to block. Only untapped creatures can block, but blocking doesn\rquote t cause creatures to tap. Other effects may also affect whether or not a set of creatures could block. See rule 500, \ldblquote Legal Attacks and Blocks.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Declare Blockers Step\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 The declare blockers step is the third step of the combat phase. The defending player declares blockers during this step. Then the active player gets priority and players may play spells and abilities. See rule 309, \ldblquote Declare Blockers Step.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Defender\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Defender is a static ability. Creatures with defender can\rquote t attack.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233\charrsid13445398 Defending Player}{\insrsid215233\charrsid14757854 \par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233\charrsid14757854 During the combat phase, the active player is }{\insrsid215233\charrsid14757854 attacking}{\insrsid215233\charrsid14757854  and is the }{\insrsid215233\charrsid14757854 attacking player}{\insrsid215233\charrsid14757854 . As the combat phase starts, the active player chooses one opponent. The chosen opponent is }{\insrsid215233\charrsid14757854 being attacked}{\insrsid215233\charrsid14757854  and is the }{\insrsid215233\charrsid14757854 defending player}{\insrsid215233\charrsid14757854 . Creatures can attack on}{\insrsid215233 ly the defending player; they can\rquote t attack other creatures. During phases other than combat, there is no defending player. See rule 306.3.\par      If the \ldblquote attack multiple players\rdblquote  option is used, there can be more than one defending player. See rule 602, \ldblquote Attack Multiple Players Option.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Delayed Triggered Ability\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 A delayed triggered ability is created by effects generated when some spells or abilities resolve. See rule 404.4.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Depend On\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 An effect is said to \ldblquote depend on\rdblquote  another if it is applied at the same time as the other effect and applying the other would change the text or the existence of the first effect, what it applies to, or what it does to any of the things it applies to. See rule 418.5, \ldblquote Interaction of Continuous Effects.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Deploy Creatures Option\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Some multiplayer games allow players to give creatures to their teammates. If the deploy creatures option is used, each creature has the ability \ldblquote \{T\}: Target teammate gains control of this creature. Play this ability only any time you could play a sorcery.\rdblquote  See rule 603, \ldblquote Deploy Creatures Option.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Destroy\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 To destroy a permanent is to move it from the in-play zone to its owner\rquote s graveyard. Regeneration or other destruction-replacement effects can replace this action. See rule 419, \ldblquote Replacement and Prevention Effects.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Discard\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 A player discards a card by putting a card from his or her hand into his or her graveyard. By default, effects that cause a player to discard a card allow the affected player to choose which card to discard. Some effects, however, require a random discard or allow another player to choose which card is discarded.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Distribute\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Distribute has its normal English meaning in the }{\b\insrsid215233 Magic}{\insrsid215233  game. If a spell or ability requires a player to distribute something (such as counters) as he or she chooses among one or more targets, or among any number of untargeted objects or players, each of these targets, objects, or players must receive at least one of whatever is being distributed. See rules 409.1e and 310.2.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Divide\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Divide has its normal English meaning in the }{\b\insrsid215233 Magic}{\insrsid215233  game. If a spell or ability requires a player to divide something (such as damage or counters) as he or she chooses among one or more targets, or any number of untargeted objects or players, each of these targets, objects, or players must receive at least one of whatever is being divided. This doesn\rquote t apply to dividing combat damage. See rules 409.1e and 310.2.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Double Strike\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Double strike is a static ability that modifies the rules for the combat damage step. Creatures with double strike deal combat damage in both the first-strike combat damage step and the normal combat damage step. See rule 502.28, \ldblquote Double Strike.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Draw\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Draw has two meanings in the }{\b\insrsid215233 Magic}{\insrsid215233  game.\par      1. A player draws a card by putting the top card of his or her library into his or her hand. If an instruction tells a player to draw more than one card, the cards are drawn one at a time. An effect may move cards from a player\rquote s library to that player\rquote s hand without the player \ldblquote drawing\rdblquote  them; this makes a difference for abilities that trigger on drawing cards or that replace card draws.\par      2. A drawn game is a game where the game ends, and there is no winner. See rule 102.4.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Draw Step\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 The draw step is the third step of the beginning phase. As the draw step begins, the active player draws a card (this game action does not use the stack). Then the active player gets priority and players may play spells and abilities. See rule 304, \ldblquote Draw Step.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Dual Land (Informal)\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Ten \ldblquote dual land\rdblquote  cards were printed in early }{\b\insrsid215233 Magic}{\insrsid215233  editions; each of these has two basic land types. For example, Taiga has the land types Forest and Mountain. Dual land cards have the default abilities of both basic land types and are treated as both by all spells and abilities that specifically refer to those types. However, they are not basic lands. A dual land card doesn\rquote t count as two lands while in play\emdash it\rquote s just one land with multiple land types. \par }{\highlight3\insrsid215233 \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 During (Obsolete)\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Some older cards used the phrase \ldblquote during [phase], [action].\rdblquote  These abilities were called \ldblquote phase abilities. In general, cards that were printed with phase abilities now have abilities that trigger at the beginning of a step or phase. \ldblquote During\rdblquote  still appears in current card text, but only in its normal English sense and not as game terminology.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Echo\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Echo is a triggered ability. \ldblquote Echo\rdblquote  means \ldblquote At the beginning of your upkeep, if this permanent came under your control since the beginning of your last upkeep, sacrifice it unless you pay its mana cost.\rdblquote  See rule 502.19, \ldblquote Echo.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Effect\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 \ldblquote Ability\rdblquote  and \ldblquote effect\rdblquote  are often confused with one another. When a spell or ability resolves, it may create one or more one-shot or continuous effects. Static abilities may create one or more continuous effects. Some effects are replacement effects or prevention effects. State-based effects are not created by spells or abilities; they are generated by specific states of the game. See rule 416, \ldblquote Effects.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Emperor\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\prauth1\prdate1721213656\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid215233 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\*\oldpprops \pard \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid215233 }{\insrsid215233 Emperor is a multiplayer variant with its own rules. The Emperor variant involves two or more teams of three players each. Each team sits together on one side of the table. Each team has one }{\insrsid215233\charrsid11615783 emperor}{\i\insrsid215233\charrsid12403447 ,}{\insrsid215233  who sits in the middle of the team. The remaining players on the team are }{\insrsid215233\charrsid11615783 generals}{\insrsid215233  whose job is to protect the emperor. In addition to the normal rules for winning and losing, a team loses if its emperor loses the game. See rule 607, \ldblquote Emperor Variant.\rdblquote \par }\pard \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid215233 {\insrsid215233      The Emperor variant uses the following default options: }{\i\insrsid215233\charrsid13445398 (a)}{\insrsid215233  The range of influence is limited to 2 for emperors and 1 for generals (see rule 601), }{\i\insrsid215233\charrsid13445398 (b)}{\insrsid215233  Emperor games use the deploy creatures option (see rule 603), and }{\i\insrsid215233\charrsid13445398 (c) }{\insrsid215233 A player can attack only an opponent seated immediately next to him or her.\par }\pard \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\insrsid215233 \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Enchant\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Enchant is a static ability, written \ldblquote Enchant [permanent or player].\rdblquote  The enchant ability restricts what an Aura spell can target and what an Aura can enchant. See rule 212.4, \ldblquote Enchantment,\rdblquote  and rule 502.45, \ldblquote Enchant.\rdblquote \par \par Enchant Player\par Auras with the \ldblquote enchant player\rdblquote  ability can target and be attached to players. Such Auras can\rquote t target permanents and can\rquote t be attached to permanents. Rules 212.4d\endash i apply to an Aura with enchant player in relation to players as they normally would for permanents. See also Aura, Enchant.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Enchantment\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Enchantment is a type. The active player can play enchantments only during his or her main phase when the stack is empty. See rule 212.4, \ldblquote Enchantments.\rdblquote  See also Aura.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Enchantment Type\par Enchantment subtypes are always a single word and are listed after a long dash: \ldblquote Enchantment \emdash  Shrine.\rdblquote  Enchantment subtypes are also called enchantment types.\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233      The list of enchantment types, updated through the }{\i\insrsid215233 Ninth Edition}{\insrsid215233  core set, is as follows: Aura, Shrine.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 End of Combat Step\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 The end of combat step is the fifth step of the combat phase. A player may play spells and abilities during this step whenever he or she has priority. See rule 311, \ldblquote End of Combat Step.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 End of Turn Step\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 This is the first step of the end phase. A player may play spells and abilities during this step whenever he or she has priority. See rule 313, \ldblquote End of Turn Step.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 End Phase\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 The end phase is the fifth and final phase of the turn. It has two steps: end of turn and cleanup. See rule 312, \ldblquote End Phase.\rdblquote \par \par Ending the Turn\par One card (Time Stop) ends the turn when its resolves. When an effect ends the turn, follow these steps in order: Remove every object on the stack from the game. Remove all attacking and blocking creatures, if any, from combat. Check state-based effects. The current step and/or phase ends. The game skips straight to the cleanup step. See rule 509, \ldblquote Ending the Turn.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Entwine\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Entwine is a static ability that functions while the spell is on the stack. \ldblquote Entwine [cost]\rdblquote  means \ldblquote You may choose to use all modes of this spell instead of just one. If you do, you pay an additional [cost].\rdblquote  When the spell resolves, if the entwine cost was paid, follow the text of each of the modes in the order they\rquote re written on the card. See rule 502.32, \ldblquote Entwine.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Epic\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Epic represents both a static ability and a delayed triggered ability. \ldblquote Epic\rdblquote  means, \ldblquote For the rest of the game, you can\rquote t play spells.\rdblquote  and \ldblquote At the beginning of each of your upkeeps, copy this spell except for its epic ability. If the spell has any targets, you may choose new targets for the copy.\rdblquote  See rule 502.44, \ldblquote Epic.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Equip\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Equip is an activated ability. \ldblquote Equip [cost]\rdblquote  means \ldblquote [cost]: Attach this Equipment to target creature you control. Play this ability only any time you could play a sorcery.\rdblquote  See rule 502.33, \ldblquote Equip,\rdblquote  and rule 212.2, \ldblquote Artifacts.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Equipment\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Some artifacts have the subtype \ldblquote Equipment.\rdblquote  These artifacts can be attached to (can \ldblquote equip\rdblquote ) creatures. They can\rquote t equip objects that aren\rquote t creatures. An Equipment is played and comes into play just like any other artifact. Equipment doesn\rquote t come into play equipping a creature. The equip keyword ability moves the Equipment onto a creature you control. (See rule 502.33, \ldblquote Equip.\rdblquote ) The creature an Equipment is attached to is called \ldblquote equipped.\rdblquote  The Equipment is attached to, or \ldblquote equips,\rdblquote  that creature.\par      An Equipment that\rquote s also a creature or an Equipment that loses the subtype \ldblquote Equipment\rdblquote  can\rquote t equip a creature. An Equipment can\rquote t equip itself. An Equipment that equips an illegal or nonexistent permanent becomes unattached from that permanent, but remains in play. (This is a state-based effect. See rule 420.)\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Evasion Ability\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Evasion abilities restrict what creatures can block an attacking creature. These are static abilities that modify the declare blockers step of the combat phase. See rule 501, \ldblquote Evasion Abilities.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Event\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Anything that happens in a game is an event. Multiple events may take place during the resolution of a spell or ability. The text of triggered abilities and replacement effects defines the event they\rquote re looking for. One \ldblquote happening\rdblquote  may be treated as a single event by one ability and as multiple events by another.\par }\pard\plain \s28\ql \li400\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin400\itap0 \i\f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\insrsid215233 Example:}{\insrsid215233  If an attacking creature is blocked by two defending creatures, this is one event for a triggered ability that reads \ldblquote Whenever [name] becomes blocked\rdblquote  but two events for a triggered ability that reads \ldblquote Whenever [name] becomes blocked by a creature.\rdblquote \par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Exchange\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\