\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 An effect is said to \ldblquote depend on\rdblquote  another if it is applied at the same time as the other effect, and applying the other would change the text or the existence of the first effect, what it applies to, or what it does to any of the things it applies to. Otherwise, the effect is considered to be independent of the first effect. See rule 418.5, \ldblquote Interaction of Continuous Effects.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Indestructible\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 If a permanent is indestructible, rules and effects can\rquote t destroy it. Such permanents are not destroyed by lethal damage, and they ignore the lethal-damage state-based effect (see rule 420.5c). Rules or effects may cause an indestructible permanent to be sacrificed, put into a graveyard, or removed from the game.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Infinity Rule (Informal)\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 There\rquote s no such thing as \ldblquote infinity\rdblquote  in }{\b\insrsid215233 Magic}{\insrsid215233  rules. Occasionally the game can get into a state where a set of actions could be repeated forever. The \ldblquote infinity rule\rdblquote  governs how to break such loops. See rule 421, \ldblquote Handling \lquote Infinite\rquote  Loops.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\out