uote Replacement and Prevention Effects.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Interrupt (Obsolete)\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Some older cards used the term \ldblquote interrupt\rdblquote  on the card\rquote s type line. All interrupt cards are now instant cards. All abilities that were played as interrupts are now played like normal activated abilities (and are mana abilities if they produce mana).\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Intervening \ldblquote If\rdblquote  Clause\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Triggered abilities with a condition directly following the trigger event (for example, \ldblquote When/Whenever/At [trigger], if [condition], [effect]\rdblquote ) check for the condition to be true as part of the trigger event; if it isn\rquote t, the ability doesn\rquote t trigger. The ability checks the condition again on resolution. If it\rquote s not satisfied, the ability does nothing. Note that this mirrors the check for legal targets. Note that this rule doesn\rquote t apply to any triggered ability with an \ldblquote if\rdblquote  condition elsewhere within its text. See rule 404.3.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Island\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 \ldblquote Island\rdblquote  is one of the five basic land types. Any land with the land type Island has the ability \ldblquote \{T\}: Add \{U\} to your mana pool.\rdblquote  See rule 212.6d.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Islandcycling\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 See Landcycling.\par \par Islandhome (Obsolete)\par Some older cards were printed with the term islandhome, which means \ldblquote This creature can\rquote t attack unless the defending player controls an Island\rdblquote  and \ldblquote When you control no Islands, sacrifice this creature.\rdblquote  Cards that previously had islandhome now simply have the two parts of islandhome written out without using the keyword.\par }\pard \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\insrsid215233 \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Islandwalk\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 See Landwalk.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Keyword Ability\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Some abilities are very common or would require too much space to define on a card. These abilities list only the name of the ability as a \ldblquote keyword\rdblquote ; sometimes reminder text summarizes the game rule. See rule 502, \ldblquote Keyword Abilities.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Kicker\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Kicker is a keyword ability with a cost and an effect. Paying a spell\rquote s kicker cost causes the spell to have an additional or alternative effect. See rule 502.21, \ldblquote Kicker.\rdblquote \par      A kicker cost is an additional cost to play a spell. You declare whether you intend to pay a spell\rquote s kicker cost at the same time you would choose the spell\rquote s mode (see rule 409.1b), and you actually pay the cost when you pay the rest of the spell\rquote s costs (see rule 409.1f\endash h). Paying a kicker cost is always optional.\par      A spell\rquote s controller chooses targets (see rule 409.1d) for a kicker effect only if he or she declared the intention to pay the kicker cost for that effect. If the spell\rquote s controller declared that he or she wouldn\rquote t pay a particular kicker cost, he or she doesn\rquote t choose the targets for the effect associated with that kicker cost.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Land\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Land is a type. Lands aren\rquote t spells and don\rquote t go on the stack; they are simply played from the hand. The active player may play a land once each turn during his or her main phase when he or she has priority and the stack is empty. If an object is both a land and another type, it can only be played as a land. It can\rquote t be played as a spell. See rule 212.6, \ldblquote Lands.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Land Type\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Land subtypes are always a single word and are listed after a long dash: \ldblquote Land \emdash  Locus, Land \emdash  Urza\rquote s Mine,\rdblquote  etc. Land subtypes are also called land types. Lands may have multiple subtypes. Note that \ldblquote basic,\rdblquote  \ldblquote legendary,\rdblquote  and \ldblquote nonbasic\rdblquote  aren\rquote t land types. See rule 212.6, \ldblquote Lands.\rdblquote  See also Basic Land Type.\par      The list of land types, updated through the }{\i\insrsid215233 Ninth Edition }{\insrsid215233 core set, is as follows:\par      Desert, Forest, Island, Lair, Locus, Mine, Mountain, Plains, Power-Plant, Swamp, Tower, Urza\rquote s\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Landcycling\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 \ldblquote Landcycling\rdblquote  is a generic term; a card\rquote s rules text usually names a specific type of land, such as \ldblquote plainscycling.\rdblquote \par      Landcycling is an activated ability. \ldblquote Plainscycling [cost]\rdblquote  means \ldblquote [Cost], Discard this card: Search your library for a plains card, reveal it, and put it into your hand. Then shuffle your library.\rdblquote  See rule 502.18, \ldblquote Cycling.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Landwalk\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 \ldblquote Landwalk\rdblquote  is a generic term; a card\rquote s rules text will give a specific property to look for, such as \ldblquote islandwalk.\rdblquote \par      Landwalk is an evasion ability. A creature with landwalk is unblockable as long as the defending player controls at least one land which has the specified subtype or supertype. See rule 502.6, \ldblquote Landwalk.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Last Known Information\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 The last known information about an object is the information that it had just before it left the zone it was in. Effects from resolving spells and abilities use last known information if the object they require information from is not in the zone it was expected to be in. See rule 413.2f.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Layer\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Continuous effects are applied in order, in six layers: (1) copy effects (see rule 503, \ldblquote Copying Objects\rdblquote ), (2) control-changing effects, (3) text-changing effects, (4) type-, subtype-, and supertype-changing effects, (5) all other continuous effects, except those that change power or toughness, and (6) power- or toughness-changing effects. See rule 418.5, \ldblquote Interaction of Continuous Effects.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Leaves Play\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 A permanent leaves play when it moves from the in-play zone to any other zone. See rule 410.10c.\par      If a token leaves play, it ceases to exist. This is a state-based effect. See rule 420.5.\par      If a permanent leaves play and later returns to play, it\rquote s treated as an entirely new permanent with no \ldblquote memory\rdblquote  of anything from its former existence. (Phasing is an exception to this; see rule 502.15, \ldblquote Phasing.\rdblquote )\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Legal Text\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Legal text (the fine print at the bottom of the card) lists the copyright information. It has no effect on game play. See rule 210, \ldblquote Legal Text.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Legend (Obsolete)\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Many creature cards were printed with the creature type \ldblquote Legend.\rdblquote  All of these cards have been given errata to have the legendary supertype. Legend is no longer a creature type. See Legendary.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Legendary\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Legendary is a supertype that may apply to any type (\ldblquote Legendary Land,\rdblquote  \ldblquote Legendary Artifact,\rdblquote  and so on).\par      If two or more permanents with the same name and the supertype legendary are in play, all are put into their owners\rquote  graveyards. This \ldblquote legend rule\rdblquote  is a state-based effect. See rule 420.5.\par      If a legendary permanent\rquote s types or subtypes change, this doesn\rquote t change its supertypes. The permanent will still be legendary.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Lethal Damage\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Lethal damage is an amount of damage greater than or equal to a creature\rquote s toughness. A creature with lethal damage, but greater than 0 toughness, is destroyed. This is a state-based effect. See rule 420.5.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Library\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 The library is the zone from which a player draws cards. When a game begins, each player\rquote s deck becomes his or her library. See rule 217.2, \ldblquote Library.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Life, Life Total\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Life total is a sort of score. Each player starts the game with 20 life. Any increase in a player\rquote s life total is considered to be gaining life. Any decrease in a player\rquote s life total is considered to be losing life. A player whose life total drops to 0 or less loses. This is a state-based effect. See rule 420.5.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 LIFO (Informal)\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 An acronym for \ldblquote Last In, First Out,\rdblquote  LIFO is the order in which spells and abilities resolve after going on the stack. The last played is resolved first. See rule 409, \ldblquote Playing Spells and Activated Abilities,\rdblquote  and rule 413, \ldblquote Resolving Spells and Abilities.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Limited Range of Influence\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Limited range of influence is an optional rule used in some multiplayer games. A player\rquote s range of influence is the maximum distance from that player, measured in player seats, that the player can affect. Players within that many seats of the player are within that player\rquote s range of influence. Objects controlled by players within a player\rquote s range of influence are also within that player\rquote s range of influence. Range of influence covers spells, abilities, effects, damage dealing, attacking, and making choices. See rule 601, \ldblquote Limited Range of Influence Option.\rdblquote \par      The limited range of influence option is always used in the Emperor variant (see rule 607), and it\rquote s often used for games involving five or more players.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Local Enchantment (obsolete)\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Some older cards used the term \ldblquote local enchantment\rdblquote  for enchantments that are attached to other permanents while they\rquote re in play. These cards now have the Aura subtype.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Lose the Game\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid215233 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 There are several ways to lose the game. A player can concede the game at any time; a player who concedes loses the game immediately. If a player\rquote s life total is 0 or less, he or she loses the game the next time a player would receive priority (this is a state-based effect; see rule 420). When a player is required to draw more cards than are left in his or her library, he or she draws the remaining cards, and then loses the game the next time a player would receive priority (this is a state-based effect; see rule 420). If a player has ten or more poison counters, he or she loses the game the next time a player would receive priority. (this is a state-based effect; see rule 420). If a player would both win and lose simultaneously, he or she loses.}{\insrsid215233\charrsid15343711  In a multiplayer game between teams, a team loses the game if all players on that team have lost.}{\insrsid215233  See rule 102, \ldblquote Winning and Losing.\rdblquote \par }\pard \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\insrsid215233 \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Madness\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Madness is a keyword that represents two abilities. \ldblquote Madness [cost]\rdblquote  means \ldblquote If a player would discard this card, that player discards it, but may remove it from the game instead of putting it into his or her graveyard\rdblquote  and \ldblquote When this card is removed from the game this way, until that player passes next, the player may play it any time he or she could play an instant by paying [cost] rather than paying its mana cost. When the player passes next, he or she puts it into his or her graveyard.\rdblquote  See rule 502.24, \ldblquote Madness.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Main Game\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 One card (Shahrazad) allows players to play a }{\b\insrsid215233 Magic}{\insrsid215233  subgame. The \ldblquote main game\rdblquote  is the game in which Shahrazad was played. See rule 506, \ldblquote Subgames.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Main Phase\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 The term \ldblquote main phase\rdblquote  comprises the first main and second main phases, also called the \ldblquote precombat\rdblquote  and \ldblquote postcombat\rdblquote  main phases. Artifact, creature, enchantment, and sorcery spells may be played only by the active player during his or her main phase, and only when the stack is empty. A player may also play one land each turn during his or her main phase.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Mana\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Mana is the energy used to play spells and is usually produced by lands. Mana is created by mana abilities (and sometimes by spells), and it can be used to pay costs immediately or can stay in the player\rquote s mana pool. See rule 406, \ldblquote Mana Abilities.\rdblquote \par      Colored mana costs, represented by colored mana symbols, can be paid only with the appropriate color of mana. Generic mana costs can be paid with any color of, or with colorless, mana. See rule 104.3.\par      The spell or ability that adds mana to a mana pool may restrict how it can be used. An ability might produce mana that can be used only to play creature spells or only to pay activation costs.\par      {\*\bkmkstart OLE_LINK2}The type of mana a permanent \ldblquote could produce\rdblquote  is the type of mana that any ability of that permanent can generate, taking into account any applicable replacement effects. If the type of mana can\rquote t be defined, there\rquote s no type of mana that that permanent could produce. The \ldblquote type\rdblquote  of mana is its color, or lack thereof (for colorless mana).\par {\*\bkmkend OLE_LINK2}\par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Mana Ability\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 A mana ability is either activated or triggered. A mana ability doesn\rquote t go on the stack\emdash it resolves immediately. See rule 411, \ldblquote Playing Mana Abilities.\rdblquote \par      A player may play an activated mana ability whenever he or she has priority and whenever a rule or effect asks for a mana payment. This is the only type of ability that can be played in the middle of playing or resolving a spell or ability. See rule 406, \ldblquote Mana Abilities.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Mana Burn\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 When a phase ends, any unused mana remaining in a player\rquote s mana pool is lost. The player loses 1 life for each mana lost this way. This is called \ldblquote mana burn.\rdblquote  See rule 300.3.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Mana Cost\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 The mana cost of a card is indicated by the mana symbols printed on its upper right corner. If a card has no mana symbols printed in its upper right corner, it has no mana cost. Land cards and face-down spells and permanents normally have no mana cost. Tokens have no mana cost unless the effect that creates them specifies otherwise. A copy of an object copies that object\rquote s mana cost. See rule 203, \ldblquote Mana Cost and Color.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Mana Pool\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 When an effect creates mana, that mana goes into the player\rquote s mana pool. From there, it can be used to pay for spells and abilities. The mana can be used immediately to pay a cost, or stored in the mana pool for use later in the phase. The mana pool is cleared at the end of each phase. See also Mana Burn.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Mana Source (Obsolete)\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Some older cards were printed with the type \ldblquote mana source.\rdblquote  All mana source cards are now instant cards. Abilities that read \ldblquote Play this ability as a mana source\rdblquote  are now mana abilities.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Mana Symbol\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 The mana symbols are \{W\}, \{U\}, \{B\}, \{R\}, \{G\}, \{X\}, \{Y\}, \{Z\} and the numerals \{0\}, \{1\}, \{2\}, \{3\}, \{4\}, and so on. See rule 104.3.\par      Each of the colored mana symbols represents one colored mana: \{W\} white, \{U\} blue, \{B\} black, \{R\} red, and \{G\} green. See rule 104.3a.\par      Numeral symbols (such as \{1\}) are generic mana costs and represent an amount of mana that can be paid with any color of, or colorless, mana. See rule 104.3b.\par      The symbols \{X\}, \{Y\} and \{Z\} represent unspecified amounts of mana; when playing a spell or activated ability with \{X\}, \{Y\}, or \{Z\} in its cost, its controller decides the value of that variable. See rule 104.3c.\par      Numeral symbols and variable symbols can also represent colorless mana if they appear in the effect of a spell or of a mana ability that reads \ldblquote add [mana symbol] to your mana pool\rdblquote  or something similar. See rule 104.3d.\par      The symbol \{0\} represents zero mana and is used as a placeholder when a spell or activated ability costs nothing to play. A spell or ability whose cost is \{0\} must still be played the same way as one with a cost greater than zero; it won\rquote t play itself automatically. See rule 104.3e.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Match\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 A match is a series of }{\b\insrsid215233 Magic}{\insrsid215233  games and is important only for tournament or league play. A two-player match usually consists of the best two of three games, or sometimes the best three of five. A multiplayer match usually consists of only one game. For more information, consult the DCI }{\b\insrsid215233 Magic}{\insrsid215233  Floor Rules (}{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst {\b\insrsid215233  HYPERLINK "http://www.wizards.com/default.asp?x=dci/utr/intro" }{\b\insrsid215233\charrsid11681739 {\*\datafield 00d0c9ea79f9bace118c8200aa004ba90b0200000003000000e0c9ea79f9bace118c8200aa004ba90b6600000068007400740070003a002f002f007700770077002e00770069007a0061007200640073002e0063006f006d002f00640065006600610075006c0074002e006100730070003f0078003d006400630069002f007500740072002f0069006e00740072006f000000}}}{\fldrslt {\cs22\b\ul\cf2\insrsid215233 www.wizards.com/default.asp?x=dci/utr/intro}}}{\insrsid215233 ).\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Maximum Hand Size\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Each player\rquote s maximum hand size is normally seven cards, though effects may modify this. As the first part of the active player\rquote s cleanup step, if he or she has too many cards in his or her hand, that player chooses and discards as many cards as needed to reduce his or her hand to its maximum size (but no more than that). See rule 314, \ldblquote Cleanup Step.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Modal, Mode\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 A spell or ability is modal if it is written \ldblquote Choose one \emdash \rdblquote  or \ldblquote [a specified player] chooses one \emdash .\rdblquote  Modal spells and abilities offer a choice of effects. A modal spell or ability\rquote s controller must choose the mode as part of playing the spell or ability or as part of putting the ability on the stack (in the case of triggered abilities). See rule 409.1b.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Modular\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Modular represents both a static ability and a triggered ability. \ldblquote Modular X\rdblquote  means \ldblquote This permanent comes into play with X +1/+1 counters on it\rdblquote  and \ldblquote When this permanent is put into a graveyard from play, you may put a +1/+1 counter on target artifact creature for each +1/+1 counter on this permanent.\rdblquote  See rule 502.35, \ldblquote Modular.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Mono Artifact (Obsolete)\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0