 his or her deck or, for cards that didn\rquote t start the game in a player\rquote s deck, the player who brought the card into the game. (Legal ownership is irrelevant to the game rules, except for the rules for ante.) The owner of a token is the controller of the effect that created it. See rule 200.1a.\par      An effect can change a permanent\rquote s controller but never its owner. (A few cards have the text \ldblquote Remove [this card] from your deck before playing if you\rquote re not playing for ante.\rdblquote  These are the only cards that can change a card\rquote s owner. See rule 217.9, \ldblquote Ante.\rdblquote )\par      A card is always put into its owner\rquote s library, hand, or graveyard, regardless of who controlled the card in its previous zone. See rule 217.1a.\par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Pass\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 To pass is to decline to take any action (usually playing a spell or ability) when you have priority. When a player passes, his or her opponent receives priority. See rule 408.1, \ldblquote Timing, Priority, and the Stack.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Pass in Succession\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 To pass in succession means that all players pass without playing any spells, playing any abilities, or performing any special actions in between. If all players pass in succession, the spell, ability, or combat damage on top of the stack resolves. If the stack is empty, the phase or step ends. See rule 408.1, \ldblquote Timing, Priority, and the Stack.\rdblquote \par \par }\pard\plain \s26\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Pay\par }\pard\plain \s27\ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f4\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid215233 Playing most spells and activated abilities requires paying costs; see rule 409, \ldblquote Playing Spells and Activated Abilities.\rdblquote  Declaring attackers (see rule 308, \ldblquote Declare Attackers Step\rdblquote ) and declaring blockers (see rule 309, \ldblquote Declare Blockers Step\rdblquote ) can also require paying costs.\par      Paying mana is done by removing the indicated amount of mana from the player\rquote s mana pool. Any time a player is asked to pay mana, mana abilities may be played. Mana abilities must be played before the costs are paid. Paying life subtracts the indicated amount of life from the player\rquote s life total. A player can\rquote t pay more mana than the amount of mana in his or her mana pool or more life than his or her life total. Zero life or zero mana can always be paid, even if the player has less than zero life.\par      To pay any cost, the player carries out the instructions specified by the spell, ability, or effect. It\rquote s illegal to attempt paying a cost when unable to successfully follow the instructions. For example, a player can\rquote t pay a cost that requires tapping a creature if that creature is already tapped.\par      Each payment applies to only one spell or ability. For example, a player can\rquote t sacrifice just one creature to play the activated abilities of two permanents that require sacrificing a creature as a cost. Also, the resolution of a spell or ability doesn\rquote t 